title: Teach-In For Democracy - Democracy Action Network  / Indivisible - Los Angeles
description:
Join us for an intensive day of learning, skill-building, and community connection designed to strengthen democratic resilience. Our One-Day Teach-In for Democracy features twenty specialized workshops organized into four themed tracks: Institutional Defense, Community Action, Movement Building, and Knowledge Foundations. Expert facilitators will guide interactive sessions covering constitutional safeguards, combating misinformation, nonviolent resistance tactics, and sustainable organizing practices. Participants can follow a single track or customize their experience, moving between sessions on legal strategies, digital organizing, inclusive coalition-building, and creative activism. The day includes a keynote address on democracy's current challenges, networking opportunities during scheduled breaks, and culminates in a collaborative action-planning session. Whether you're a seasoned activist or newly engaged, you'll leave equipped with practical tools, deeper understanding, and vital connections to defend and strengthen democratic values in your community.

Opening Remarks (9:00 AM - 9:15 AM)
Welcome and introduction to the day's objectives

Morning Session 1 (9:15 AM - 10:15 AM)
Track A: Constitutional Safeguards Under Pressure Understanding threats to democratic institutions and constitutional protections

Track B: Beyond the Ballot: Year-Round Civic Engagement Practical tools for sustained democratic participation

Track C: Building Bridges Across Political Divides Techniques for finding common ground with unlikely allies

Track D: Understanding Authoritarianism: Recognizing the Warning Signs Historical patterns and contemporary indicators of democratic backsliding

Morning Break (10:15 AM - 10:30 AM)
Refreshments and networking

Morning Session 2 (10:30 AM - 11:30 AM)
Track A: Digital Democracy: Combating Misinformation Skills for identifying and countering misinformation

Track B: The Power of Local: Democracy in Your Community Engaging with local government and building community resilience

Track C: Nonviolent Resistance: Historical Lessons for Today Case studies from successful nonviolent movements

Track D: Legal Strategies for Democratic Defense Understanding the role of litigation in protecting democratic norms

Morning Break (11:30 AM - 11:45 AM)
Refreshments and networking

Morning Session 3 (11:45 AM - 12:45 PM)
Track A: Democracy in the Workplace: Economic Justice Connecting democratic values to economic power structures

Track B: Strategic Communications for Movement Building Messaging techniques that build broad support

Track C: From Protest to Policy: Creating Lasting Change Translating grassroots energy into policy outcomes

Track D: Art and Culture for Democratic Renewal Using creative expression to strengthen democratic movements

Lunch & Keynote (12:45 PM - 1:45 PM)
"Democracy at a Crossroads: Why This Moment Matters" Featured speaker addressing the current state of American democracy

Afternoon Break (1:45 PM - 2:00 PM)
Refreshments and networking

Afternoon Session 1 (2:00 PM - 3:00 PM)
Track A: Sustaining the Movement: Preventing Activist Burnout Practices for maintaining activist well-being and sustainable organizing

Track B: Inclusive Democracy: Engaging Marginalized Communities Strategies for building a movement that represents all Americans

Track C: Defending Elections: Protecting Voting Rights Understanding threats to electoral integrity and how to counter them

Track D: Digital Organizing: Tools and Tactics Leveraging technology for effective movement building

Afternoon Break (3:00 PM - 3:15 PM)
Refreshments and networking

Afternoon Session 2 (3:15 PM - 4:15 PM)
Track A: Media Engagement: Getting Democratic Messages Heard Working effectively with traditional and new media

Track B: Faith Communities and Democracy Engaging religious institutions in democratic renewal

Track C: Youth Organizing for Democratic Future Strategies for engaging young people in democratic activism

Track D: Building Rural-Urban Coalitions Bridging geographic divides to strengthen democratic movements

Closing Plenary (4:30 PM - 5:00 PM)
"Building the Movement: Next Steps Together" Interactive session where participants integrate learnings and develop action plans

Schedule Notes:
Each workshop is one hour in length

15-minute breaks between sessions allow for networking and transition time

Participants can attend up to 5 different workshops plus the closing plenary

Workshops are organized in thematic tracks but participants may mix and match

Materials and resources from all workshops will be available digitally for participants

Students in Texas public schools have the same constitutional right to religious freedom as anyone else. Despite this, politicians and far-right extremists continually attempt to undermine the separation of church and state in public school classrooms. 


What's the Bluebonnet Curriculum?
The state’s new K-5 Bluebonnet curriculum — which schools would be financially incentivized to use — overemphasizes Christianity. Please join us for an organizing zoom call ahead of our second town hall leg in Southern Idaho. On May 13th, we’ll be meeting at 5:30pm to discuss the logistics of pulling off a successful round of town halls to help inform the public of the dangers of vouchers and the need for people to get involved in this important fight.

During the 2025 legislative session, Idaho lawmakers passed House Bill 93 and enacted a $50 million school-voucher program. For the first time in state history, Idaho tax dollars will be used to subsidize the cost of tuition for private-school families. 

The special-interest groups promoting vouchers have made clear that the $50 million program is only the beginning. During next year’s legislative session, they intend to remove the $50-million cap and expand the program to all private-school families, including the wealthy, at an estimated cost of $339 million per year.
 
Such a massive expansion of vouchers would bankrupt Idaho and drain millions from public schools. For the benefit of a small number of private-school families, it would defund the public education system that serves 94% of Idaho’s kids. 

It may be inevitable that the legislature tries to expand House Bill 93, but it is not inevitable that they will succeed. To stop this attack on public schools, we need to get organized. Please sign up if you can make it and we hope to see you soon!

title: We Are The Bridge: Rise For Racial Justice Rally
description:
Remember George Floyd.

Remember the life that was stolen because of systemic racism and state sanctioned violence.

Remember how we responded, transforming our outrage and grief into an uprising that rocked the entire nation.

Remember that we’re not done. Our journey has only just begun.

To amplify the movement for Black lives, Brown Hope has convened a grassroots movement called We Are The Bridge: Rise for Racial Justice, a week of action between May 15 — May 24 in recognition of George Floyd’s murder five years ago. This week of action features a series of community gatherings, culminating in a historic rally on May 24th at Revolution Hall and a peaceful march through downtown Portland and the Burnside Bridge.

We march for George Floyd. Breonna Taylor. Quanice Hayes. Kendra James. Eric Garner. Mike Brown. And so many others. We march because this injustice and suffering should never happen again. It should not take the deaths of more Black people for our elected and business leaders to do the right thing.

A grassroots coalition of Portland-based organizations have formed We Are The Bridge: Rise for Racial Justice— including Brown Hope, 50501 Portland, the Coalition of Black Men, the Oregon Working Families Party, Outside In, SURJ PDX, BIPOC Rise Moor Healing Center, Radical Rest, Veterans For Peace PDX Chapter 72, Restorative Roots Project, and Momentum Alliance. Together, we are calling for immediate action to expand opportunities for our local Black community to thrive— economically, socially, and spiritually.

Here’s the complete list of events organized for our week of action:

Nonviolence and De-escalation Training: 6pm on Thursday, May 15 at openHAUS (5020 NE MLK Blvd). Facilitated by the Portland Peace Team, this training teaches how to foster peace during moments of conflict using the CLARA de-escalation method.

Community Grief Circle:12:30pm on Saturday, May 17 at Alberta Park (1905 NE Killingsworth St). Experienced facilitators will lead activities that help attendees release emotional wounds connected to George Floyd’s murder and racial violence. Concludes with an optional community potluck.

Know Your Rights Training: 6pm on Thursday, May 22nd, Online. Facilitated by the National Lawyers Guild, the workshop covers constitutional rights related to activism and police interactions at first amendment events.

We Are The Bridge Rally and March: noon on Saturday, May 24th at Revolution Hall (1300 SE Stark St). A rally featuring Black and Indigenous leaders, followed by a peaceful march through downtown Portland with a moment of silence on Burnside Bridge.

As we remember George Floyd’s life and legacy, we must acknowledge that we have the responsibility to act. We Are The Bridge is encouraging supporters to help us build power by donating to local racial justice organizations and promoting the campaign on social media by using the hashtags #BlackLivesMatter and #BeTheBridge.

In 2020, Portland became a beacon of hope for the whole nation and the entire world thanks to 100 days of sustained action in solidarity with Black lives. This year, We Are The Bridge: Rise For Racial Justice is a collective antidote to the disease of moral bankruptcy currently plaguing our country. By participating in this week of action, we can make 2025 a defining year for Portland and our commitment to justice.

We are the heartbeat of this movement. Let’s work together to inspire a lasting movement of change.

For more information, visit: https://linktr.ee/BrownHope

#BlackLivesMatter #BeTheBridge

- Gleaning is collecting leftover crops from farms that would otherwise go to waste. These fresh fruits and vegetables are then donated to food banks and hunger relief groups.

#### 2. Who can attend?

- All are welcome—no prior experience needed! Perfect for families, small groups, or anyone looking to serve. (Kids must be with an adult.)

#### 3. Are tools provided?
- Yes! We’ll supply any tools and bags you’ll need to glean.

#### 4. What if it rains?

- We’ll monitor the weather and let you know if anything changes. Safety first!

#### 5. Where does the food go?

- All the produce goes directly to local food banks and community partners feeding those in need.

#### 6. How can I stay in the loop?

- For event updates, visit: https://www.mobilize.us/endhunger/

#### 7. Other FAQs :

- NO smoking, NO pets

Join Next Up Action Fund as we knock doors to support Portland Public School Board Candidates Jorge Bautista Sanchez for Zone 5 and Rashelle Chase Miller for Zone 4 ✨ We'll also be support Stephanie Engelsman for Zone 6 and Christy Splitt was Zone 4 

We'll make sure everyone is trained on how to canvass using MiniVan and feel prepared to talk through vote plans with voters while sharing about Jorge and Rashelle's prioritizes!

More about the candidates:

Jorge Sanchez Bautista is running for Portland School Board in NE Portland (Zone 5, but elected citywide!) to ensure students are a priority and that we are fully funding public education. A native Portlander, he was raised in the Cully neighborhood and is a student, community organizer, and an educational advocate. With experience passing legislative bills, advocating for change, and being a student in Portland Public Schools all of his life, he is ready to bring change and advocate for all.

Rashelle Chase-Miller is a mom, an early childhood educator, a literacy advocate and a fifth-generation North Portlander. With over 25 years of experience in early childhood education, she's dedicated her career to promoting equitable access to high-quality learning experiences for all children and their families. Currently, she serve as the statewide Program Director for SMART Reading, where she's committed to fostering a love of reading among children across Oregon by helping them build their own home libraries while providing reading support.
